{"author":{"id":"10eadc33269d0f2388759c2d3a1a82229225e32af3cb4439329fa60ad155db88"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1517596609,"nonce":"k0AGXU0p0YjXas/7mFSHOAia1wo=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWUyOTM5ODMzMTk=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/1703","origin":"github"},"title":"ENCODE IDR guidelines and IDR tool","message":"Encode has [IDR ](https://www.encodeproject.org/data-standards/terms/#concordance) guidelines for ChIP-seq or ATAC-seq replicates. These guidelines require calling \"pseudoreplicates\", which require splitting the BAM files for each replicate into two and calling peaks on the split BAM files. The guidelines also use \"pooled-pseudoreplicates\"; merging the replicate BAMs together, splitting the merged BAM into two, and calling peaks. At the end of this, there should be peaksets for peaks on original replicates, peaksets on self-pseudoreplicates, and peaksets on pooled pseudoreplicates. IDR analysis is then carried out on matching peaksets. [This ](https://sites.google.com/site/anshulkundaje/projects/idr/deprecated) page can offer a more in depth explanation; the pipeline is deprecated but the principles are still accurate. \n\nIs it feasible to configure the IDR Galaxy tool so that it takes in 2 BAM files (replicates) as input and outputs IDR matched peaks for the various pseudo-replicates? Currently, the IDR tool takes in 2 peak files and outputs a set of peaks that pass the IDR threshold.","files":null}]}